Converts an IPv4 address into a `u32` representation using native byte order.

Although IPv4 addresses are big-endian, the `u32` value will use the target platformâ€™s native byte order. That is, the `u32` value is an integer representation of the IPv4 address and not an integer interpretation of the IPv4 addressâ€™s big-endian bitstring. This means that the `u32` value masked with `0xffffff00` will set the last octet in the address to 0, regardless of the target platformâ€™s endianness.

